<title>Trevorese Tutorial</title>
<link href="styles.css" rel="stylesheet"/>
</head>
<body class="tutorial-body"><h1>Trevorese Skeleton Grammar</h1>
<div class="section-h2"><div class="collapsible-header">The Trevorese Word</div><div class="collapsible-content">
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Sounds</div><div class="collapsible-content">
Each Trevorese syllable has the form CV[N], where C is a consonant, V is a vowel, and N is the sound “ng”.
<h4>Vowels</h4>
Trevorese has the five cardinal vowels <b>/aiuoe/</b>, as well as three diphthongs <b>/ai/</b>,<b>/au/</b>, and <b>/oi/</b>, which are pronounced exactly like the combination of the two vowels they are made of.
<h4>Consonants</h4>
Trevorese has 12 simple consonants, <b>/w/</b>,<b>/y/</b>,<b>/m/</b>,<b>/b/</b>,<b>/g/</b>,<b>/d/</b>,<b>/n/</b>,<b>/s/</b>,<b>/p/</b>,<b>/k/</b>,<b>/t/</b>,<b>/l/</b> and 11 compound consonants, <b>/ny/</b>,<b>/mw/</b>,<b>/bw/</b>,<b>/gw/</b>,<b>/dw/</b>,<b>/sw/</b>,<b>/pw/</b>,<b>/kw/</b>,<b>/tw/</b>. The compound consonants are pronounced exactly like the combination of their two constituents, e.g. /<b>k</b>ik/ sounds like “<b>k</b>ick” and /<b>kw</b>ik/ sounds like “<b>qu</b>ick”.
<h4>Phonotactics</h4>
A variety of possible syllables are never used by Trevorese, as they are deemed too easy to mistake with other syllables. For example, <span class="wrong">*nyi</span> and <span class="wrong">*yi</span> are too easy to mistake for <span class="surface">ni</span> and <span class="surface">i</span>, respectively. Diphthongs plus nasal coda, like <span class="wrong">*bwaing</span> or <span class="wrong">*saung</span>, are forbidden as they are deemed too hard to pronounce.
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Atoms</div><div class="collapsible-content">
There are under 200 basic words from which all other words are built. These are called atoms. They all have the form consonant+vowel[+optional ng]. The simplest atom would simply have consonant+vowel, e.g. <span class="surface">ma</span>, or <span class="surface">su</span>. Atoms representing slightly more complex concepts use more use of compound consonants, diphthongs, and the nasal coda, e.g. <span class="surface">yau</span>, <span class="surface">kwe</span>, or <span class="surface">nang</span>.

There are six special atoms that start with a vowel, representing the most basic concepts of <span class="gloss">this</span>, <span class="gloss">that</span>, <span class="gloss">all</span>, <span class="gloss">what</span>, and <span class="gloss">foreign_marker</span>. These are usually not used in compound words.
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Compounds</div><div class="collapsible-content">
Most words in Trevorese are compounds, composed of multiple syllables. It is always unambiguous what atoms a compound is made of. Here are some examples:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>of/from</td>
<td><span class="gloss">of</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>from the back</td>
<td><span class="gloss">of-back</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>to follow (go from the back)</td>
<td><span class="gloss">of-back-go</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>dog (a following/loyal animal)</td>
<td><span class="gloss">of-back-go-animal</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



If the compound is on the longer side, it can be written with a hyphen to show the etymology better:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>dog</td>
<td><span class="gloss">of-back-go</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>forest</td>
<td><span class="gloss">big-plant-place</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>wolf (forest-dog)</td>
<td><span class="gloss">big-plant-place_of-back-go</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div></div></div></div></div><div class="section-h2"><div class="collapsible-header">Grammar 1: the basics</div><div class="collapsible-content">
The following introduces <span class="english">English,</span><span class="gloss">Gloss,</span> and <span class="surface">Trevorese</span> forms. The gloss is just Trevorese using (approximate) English words, so it is easier to see exactly what’s going on. There may also be some loose literal translations in &lt; angle brackets &gt;. These are loose translations of the Trevorese into English so you can understand more or less how the construction words. For instance:

<ul>
<li>English: <span class="english">I saw the black cat</span></li>
<li>Loose translation:  &lt;I did see the cat like blackness &gt; </li>
<li>gloss: <span class="gloss">me back do see cat like dark-color</span></li>
<li>Trevorese: <span class="surface">mi ya du si mau se nobailang</span></li>
</ul>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Nouns</div><div class="collapsible-content">

There is no distinction between <span class="english">a</span> and <span class="english">the.</span> Therefore:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>a cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



If you want to specify a particular one, you can use quantifiers like <span class="gloss">this</span>, <span class="gloss">what</span>, and <span class="gloss">what</span>:<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>this cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>that cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>what cat?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">what</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span>?</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



Now let’s introduce a simple verb: <span class="gloss">be</span>. For any verb in the present tense, you need to use the word <span class="gloss">do</span> to mark that it is a verb:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>this cat <b>is</b> a friend</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">be</span> <span class="gloss">love-person</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>a dog <b>is</b> an animal</td>
<td><span class="gloss">dog</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">be</span> <span class="gloss">person</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



To negate this, just add <span class="gloss">no</span> right before the verb:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>that cat <b>is not<b></b> a friend</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">no</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">be</span> <span class="gloss">love-person</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Plurals</div><div class="collapsible-content">
You may notice that in the previous examples, the word for <span class="english">cats</span> was the same as the word for <span class="english">cat.</span> In Trevorese, the plural looks the same as the singular! If you speak a European language, you may think this will cause ambiguity. However, usually the quantifier makes it unambiguous as to whether the noun is plural or not. For instance, with a quantifier like <span class="english">many</span> or <span class="english">sixty-seven</span>, you already know that the noun following it is plural.  This said, there are a few examples of when context alone is not enough to determine whether something is plural. For example, consider the sentence <span class="english">I was trying to sleep when I heard some cat meow</span> vs <span class="english">I was trying to sleep when I heard some <b>cats</b> meow</span>; or  <span class="english">this cat is chonky</span> vs <span class="english"><b>these</b> <b>cats</b> are chonky</span>.

In these cases, you can use the word <span class="gloss">number</span> to mark the plural:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>A dog</td>
<td><span class="gloss">dog</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>dog<b>s</b> [two or more]</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">number</span> <span class="gloss">dog</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>that dog is a friend</td>
<td><span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">dog</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">love-person</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>those</b> dogs are friends</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">that</span> <span class="gloss">number</span> <span class="gloss">dog</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">love-person</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



Literally, this just means “group”. It goes before the noun, because it is a quantifier, just like <span class="gloss">this</span> or <span class="gloss">that</span>.
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Adjectives 1</div><div class="collapsible-content">
Let’s look at some <b>modifiers,</b> aka adjectives/adverbs. In Trevorese, there is no difference between nouns and adjectives! You just say that a noun is “like'” another noun with <span class="gloss">like</span>:<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>the cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the black cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss">dark-color</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat is black</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss">dark-color</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat is talkative</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>this cat is friendly</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss">love-being</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>that cat is not friendly</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">no</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss">love-being</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>a friend is friendly</td>
<td><span class="gloss">love-being</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss">love-being</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>what dog is cat-like?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">what</span> <span class="gloss">dog</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>those dogs friendly</td>
<td><span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">number</span> <span class="gloss">dog</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss">love-being</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



Another way of thinking about <span class="gloss">like</span> is <span class="english">that’s:</span> “the black cat” is expressed as &lt;the cat <b>that’s</b> black&gt;.

With multiple adjectives, put a <span class="gloss">like</span> before each one:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>this cat <b>is friendly, talkative, and doglike</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">love-person</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">talk</span>, <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">dog</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Verbs 1</div><div class="collapsible-content">
We already saw the verb <span class="gloss">do be</span>. Let’s talk more about verbs. There are not truly verbs in this language; you can just “do” a noun. Just like in English, you can substitute <span class="english">I squat</span> with <span class="english">I do a squat</span>, or <span class="english">I boop</span> with <span class="english">I do a boop</span>:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>the cat <b>is talking</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat <b>is not talking</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">no</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">talk</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



While we’re at it, let’s learn the tenses. In Trevorese, there are three basic tenses: past, present, and future. They are expressed with <span class="gloss">back</span>, <span class="gloss">do</span>, and <span class="gloss">front</span>:<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>the cat <b>talked</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat <b>is talking</b> / the cat <b>talks</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat <b>will talk</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">front</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">talk</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



Past, present, future – that’s it!

Now that we can form a full sentence, let’s go back to adjectives. Adjectives go after the thing they modify:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>the friendly cat is talking</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">good-person</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat is talking <b>friendlily/in a friendly way</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">good-person</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>that cat is talking <b>unfriendlily</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">no</span> <span class="gloss-emph">good-person</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the <b>black</b> dog is talking <b>in a friendly, cat-like way</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">dog</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">dark-color</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">good-person</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>he sings <b>sweetly, like a small bird</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">good-sound</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">sugar</span>, <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">air-animal</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">small</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>he spoke to me <b>like a child</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">small-person</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


Notes:
the penultimate sentence is somewhat ambiguous in Trevorese, but contextually it’s clear.
the last sentence is ambiguous in English and Trevorese both.

</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Pronouns</div><div class="collapsible-content">
At this point we can talk about pronouns:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>I / me</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>you</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>he / she / him / her / it</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



The plural forms of these are formed with <span class="gloss">number</span>, just like the plural of a noun:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>we / us</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">number</span> <span class="gloss">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>you all</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">number</span> <span class="gloss">you</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>they / them</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">number</span> <span class="gloss">this</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



Here are examples using them in sentences:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><b>I</b> am a cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">me</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>I</b> am black</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">me</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">dark-color</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>I</b> am talking</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">me</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



You may notice that <span class="gloss">this</span> means both he / she, as well as “this”! Therefore, the following are all valid translations, and need context to tell apart:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><b>he</b> is a black cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">dark-color</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>she</b> is a black cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">dark-color</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>this</b> is a black cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">dark-color</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


Similarly, these two sentences are the same in Trevorese:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>this cat is black</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">dark-color</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>this black cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">dark-color</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">“Thing”</div><div class="collapsible-content">
Any verb, noun, or adjective can be replaced with “thing” if the context is clear. For instance:
<ul>
<li><span class="english">We were thinging football</span></li>
<li><span class="english">I didn’t hear the thing you just thinged</span></li>
</ul>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Prepositions</div><div class="collapsible-content">
Prepositions are words that say how two things are related. For instance, you can say that the dog is <span class="english">behind</span> the cat, <span class="english">over</span> the cat, <span class="english">in</span> the cat, <span class="english">for</span> the cat; or that it is woofing <span class="english">at</span> the cat, or <span class="english">with</span> the cat, or <span class="english">by</span> the cat.

There are no true prepositions in Trevorese – everything is ultimately a noun. When you would use a preposition to describe where something is in English, just use the noun for corresponding location in Trevorese. If a dog is <span class="english">on</span> the roof, you say that the dog is <span class="gloss">surface</span> the roof. If you are going <span class="english">to</span> the store, you are going <span class="gloss">direction</span> the store; and if you are going <span class="english">from</span> the store, you are going <span class="gloss">of</span> the store. If the dog jumps <span class="english">onto</span> the roof, it jumps <span class="gloss">direction</span><span class="gloss">surface</span> the roof.

The following sections give details about how common prepositions are used.
<h4>Possession with “of”</h4>
Let’s start with <span class="gloss">of</span>, aka the word meaning <span class="english">belonging/possession</span>. This word indicates possession:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>This is <b>my</b> dog</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">dog</span> <span class="gloss-emph">of</span> <span class="gloss-emph">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>This is my dog<b>’s toy</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">play-thing</span> <span class="gloss-emph">of</span> <span class="gloss-emph">dog</span> <span class="gloss">of</span> <span class="gloss">me</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



The independent forms <span class="english">mine/yours/ours/hers/its/his/theirs</span> are handled simply by dropping the subject, as in Chinese:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>This is <b>mine</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss-emph">of</span> <span class="gloss-emph">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>This is <b>my</b> dog. Where is <b>yours?</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">dog</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss-emph">of</span> <span class="gloss-emph">me</span>. <span class="gloss-emph">of</span> <span class="gloss-emph">you</span> <span class="gloss">what</span> <span class="gloss">place</span>?</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div><span class="gloss">of</span> can also mean “from”, as we will see in the next section.
<h4>Coexistence with “with”</h4>
The word <span class="gloss">with</span> is very straightforward. It is used just as <span class="english">with</span> or <span class="english">and</span> in English:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>The person is <b>with</b> the cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">person</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss-emph">with</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Come <b>with</b> me!</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">go</span> <span class="gloss-emph">with</span> <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">please</span>!</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I see a dog <b>and</b> a cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">see</span> <span class="gloss">dog</span> <span class="gloss-emph">with</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>he mixed water <b>with</b> soil</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">with-do</span> <span class="gloss">water</span> <span class="gloss-emph">with</span> <span class="gloss">dirt</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>he mixed water <b>with</b> a stick</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">use</span> <span class="gloss">stick</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">with-do</span> <span class="gloss">water</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


Note that in the last example, the English “with” here is an instrumental marker in English, and actually a quite different meaning from the normal meaning. For the normal meaning of “with”, this would mean “He and a shovel were digging a hole”!

<h4>Basic Prepositions of movement</h4><div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>She drove <b>to</b> the store</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">drive</span> <span class="gloss-emph">direction</span> <span class="gloss">store</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>She drove <b>from</b> the store</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">drive</span> <span class="gloss-emph">of</span> <span class="gloss">store</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>She drove <b>through</b> the store</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">drive</span> <span class="gloss-emph">through</span> <span class="gloss">store</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>She was driving <b>at</b> the store</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">drive</span> <span class="gloss-emph">place</span> <span class="gloss">store</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div><h4>Spatial prepositions</h4>
English has a lot of prepositions for how two objects can be related. The snake can be <b>in front of</b> the dog, <b>near</b> the dog, <b>inside</b> the dog, <b>above</b> the dog, <b>on</b> the dog, or <b>by the side</b> of the dog. Some of these change if there is movement: for instance, after the snake goes <b>into</b> the dog it is <b>inside</b> the dog.

In Trevorese, these prepositions are simply expressed as one of the basic prepositions of movement (usually <span class="gloss">direction)</span> plus the location relative to the object. Let’s look at a few examples. In these examples, we’ll break them up by whether the movement is static (happening in one location), or as a movement to- or from that location:


location noun: inside
