<td>through</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div><h4>Temporal prepositions</h4>
Prepositions of time are expressed with the same words as those of space. Imagine yourself as a box where the future stretches out in front of you and the past behind. Now imagine that you yourself are an event in time. You see another event in the future, in front of you. This event happens <b>after</b> you in time — so in this spatial metaphor, it happens <b>in front of</b> you. You happen <b>before</b> it — so, spatially, you happen <b>behind</b> it. Say there is another event that starts before you and ends after you. You happen <b>during</b> that event — spatially, you happen <b>in</b> it. And if you (the event) started at the same time as the other event and continue on forwards in time — aka you happen <b>since</b> that event — spatially,  you happen <b>starting</b> at that event.{{languages do this in a variety of ways. For instance, in English, you also see a timeline with the future stretching out in front of you, but the perspective is with respect to you, looking at two other events, rather than from the perspective of the event (grammatical subject) itself.  So if you see two events, the one that is closer to you happens before the one that is further away, which is why English “before” means “in front of”, rather than “behind”.}}


<h4>Prepositions in verb phrases</h4>
Many Indo-European verbs have prepositions built into them, and it causes considerable chaos for learners to master them. In Trevorese, these prepositions are generally absent:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>I <b>worked on</b> a project</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">hard-do</span> <span class="gloss">project</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>What are you <b>talking about</b>?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">talk</span> <span class="gloss">what</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Which person are you <b>talking about</b>?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">talk</span> <span class="gloss">what</span> <span class="gloss">person</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>he <b>depends on</b> me</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">depend</span> <span class="gloss">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>She <b>believes in</b> God</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">truth-think</span> <span class="gloss">God</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Look at</b> this!</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">see</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">please</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>what are you <b>looking for</b>?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">seek</span> <span class="gloss">what</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>They <b>listen to</b> music</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">number</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">sound-see</span> <span class="gloss">good-sound</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I am <b>coping with</b> loss.</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">cope</span> <span class="gloss">loss</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



An exception is verbs that take indirect objects with the preposition <span class="english">to,</span> like <span class="english">talk to</span>. These are explained in the section on indirect objects.

In some cases where English has different meanings for different prepositions, Trevorese has different verbs. In these cases you’ll notice that English also generally offers us easy synonyms:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>What are you <b>looking at</b>?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">see</span> <span class="gloss">what-thing</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>What are you <b>looking for</b>?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">seek</span> <span class="gloss">what-thing</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>What are you<b>looking up</b>?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">seek</span> <span class="gloss">what-thing</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>What are you<b>looking after</b>?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">care</span> <span class="gloss">what-thing</span>?</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


In other cases there is some ambiguity:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>She <b>believes</b> me</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">truth-think</span> <span class="gloss">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>She <b>believes in</b> God</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">truth-think</span> <span class="gloss">God</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>She <b>believes in</b> me</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">trust</span> <span class="gloss">me</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


Notice however that even in English, <span class="english">believe in</span> has a different meaning when applied to God versus to me! Really, there is ambiguity everywhere in all languages, but context clears almost everything up!

