<div class="section-h2"><div class="collapsible-header">Grammar 2: more basics</div><div class="collapsible-content">
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Commands and yes/no questions</div><div class="collapsible-content">
Questions and commands  are formed by adding the particles <span class="gloss">what</span> and <span class="gloss">please</span> at the end of the sentence:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>You talk to the cat.</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">direction</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Do you talk to the cat?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">direction</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">what</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Talk to the cat!</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">direction</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">please</span>!</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Quantifiers and the wh- words</div><div class="collapsible-content">
    This <span class="gloss">what</span> that we have been using to form questions is what is called (in Trevorese grammar) a quantifier. Quantifiers are little words that tell us something about the way that an object exists. They come before the noun. The quantifiers we have seen so far are <span class="gloss">this</span>, <span class="gloss">that</span>, <span class="gloss">what</span>, <span class="gloss">number</span>, no</span>, and numbers, like 67.

Two more words that fall in this category in English are <span class="english">some</span> and <span class="english">any</span>. For the most part these are entirely unnecessary in Trevorese:

TODO fix this should be a 3,1 table

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><b>some</b>one is coming!</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">any</span><span class="gloss">one</span> <span class="gloss">is</span> <span class="gloss">coming</span>!</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>A person is coming!</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">person</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">this-go</span>!</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I want to live <b>some</b>where warm.</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">want</span> <span class="gloss">to</span> <span class="gloss">live</span> <span class="gloss-emph">any</span><span class="gloss">where</span> <span class="gloss">warm</span>.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I want to live in a warm place.</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">want</span> <span class="gloss">live</span> <span class="gloss-emph">place</span> <span class="gloss">so</span> <span class="gloss">middle-hot</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>You say <b>some</b>thing</td>
<td><span class="gloss">You</span> <span class="gloss">say</span> <span class="gloss-emph">any</span><span class="gloss">thing</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>You say <b>a</b> thing</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss-emph">thing</span>.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



However, if you need to stress the non-specificness of something, you can use <span class="gloss">no-specific</span>:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Which cat do you talk to?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">direction</span> <span class="gloss">what</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Oh, just <b>some cat</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">that</span>, <span class="gloss">self</span> <span class="gloss-emph">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">no-specific</span>.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Please just say <b>anything!</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss-emph">thing</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">no-specific</span> <span class="gloss">please</span> <span class="gloss">self</span>!</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>




There is one more of these, <span class="gloss">all,</span> meaning <span class="english">every/each</span> or <span class="english">complete:</span><div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>You know <b>every</b>thing</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">know</span> <span class="gloss-emph">all</span> <span class="gloss">thing</span>.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>You like <b>all</b> cats</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">all</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



With these in our arsenal, we can now express an amazing range of things. Let’s introduce some more words:
