<td>everyone</td>
<td><span class="gloss">all</span> <span class="gloss">person</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



Look closely at these. In English, we have so many different words for these concepts, and it hides how similar they all are! It is common for a language to be like English in this way, and have some collection of concepts from different roots and languages, such that the true structure is hidden. However, several other languages actually make these relations perfectly clear — for instance Telugu, what uses exactly the structure described above!

</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">an adjective can be a whole sentence! (relative clauses)</div><div class="collapsible-content">
Let’s get back to adjectives. As you recall, adjectives are just formed by saying that a noun is <b>like</b> another noun:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>a cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>a black cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">dark-color</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>a little baby</td>
<td><span class="gloss">new-person</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">small</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



But what if you want to say that the cat is like something more complicated than a single noun? What if you want to say that the cat is like a little baby?
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>a cat <b>that is like</b> a little baby</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss">new-person</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">small</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



You can do that too! In fact, you can put a full sentence in front of the <span class="gloss">like,</span> as long as it describes how that cat is:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>The cat I saw yesterday</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">see</span> (this) <span class="gloss">last-day</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat that is meowing sadly</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> (this) <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">cat-sound</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">sad</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat that is meowing sadly at me</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> (this) <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">cat-sound</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">sad</span> <span class="gloss">direction</span> <span class="gloss">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat that I think is meowing sadly at me</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">think</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">cat-sound</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">sad</span> <span class="gloss">direction</span> <span class="gloss">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat that I don’t know where he is</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">no</span> <span class="gloss">know</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">is</span> <span class="gloss">what</span> <span class="gloss">place</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



Note that according to the “proper” English grammar, this last example is impossible to express. As you can see, “like” is a very powerful tool! It is used anywhere English uses “that” to start a relative clause.

NB: The <span class="gloss">this</span> is optional here, and usually left out; it is included in parentheses for completeness


</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Comparative and Superlative</div><div class="collapsible-content">
When we compare things in Trevorese, we can think of them as if they are on a mountain, with the higher ones up being more of that adjective, and the one on the top being the most of that adjective!

We can do this with <span class="gloss">like</span> clauses. Here are the relevant words:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>over</td>
<td><span class="gloss">over</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>under</td>
<td><span class="gloss">down</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



To make a comparative statement like <span class="english">I am bigger than you</span>, we say something like &lt;I am big over you&gt;, similar to how in Nigerian Pidgin you would say “I am big past you”:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>That cat is sweet<b>er</b> than this cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">That</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">sugar</span> <span class="gloss-emph">over</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>My cat is bigg<b>er</b> than your dog</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">of</span> <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">big</span> <span class="gloss-emph">over</span> <span class="gloss">dog</span> <span class="gloss">of</span> <span class="gloss">you</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



Consider the following argument between two people about which cat is sweeter:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>this cat is sweet</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">sugar</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Yes, he is <b>very sweet</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">truth</span>, <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">big</span> <span class="gloss-emph">sugar</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>But that cat is <b>sweeter than</b> this cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">against</span> <span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">sugar</span> <span class="gloss-emph">over</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>That cat is <b>sweeter</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">sugar</span> <span class="gloss-emph">over</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>This cat is <b>less sweet than</b> that cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">sugar</span> <span class="gloss-emph">down</span> <span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>That cat is<b> much sweeter than</b> this cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">big</span> <span class="gloss-emph">sugar</span> <span class="gloss-emph">over</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>This cat is <b>much less sweet than</b> that cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">big</span> <span class="gloss-emph">sugar</span> <span class="gloss-emph">down</span> <span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



Hopefully, they will eventually reach a conclusion like the following:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>That cat is <b>as sweet as</b> this cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">sugar</span> <span class="gloss-emph">one-kind</span> <span class="gloss-emph">of</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



On the other hand, they might start using the superlative:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>That cat is <b>the sweetest</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">over-thing</span> <span class="gloss-emph">sugar</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>That cat is <b>the least sweet</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">down-thing</span> <span class="gloss-emph">sugar</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


Note: you could also express this as “that cat like <b>sweetness beyond all</b>”, though this is less idiomatic.

</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Verbs 3: Verbs acting on other verbs: tenses and modals</div><div class="collapsible-content">
We have seen how to use a verb with a noun as its object:
normal verb: <span class="english">I see a dog</span> (the object of <span class="english">see</span> is <span class="english">dog</span> is a noun)
Now let’s talk about verbs that act on other verbs, which we can call “modal verbs”:
modal verb: <span class="english">I can sing</span> (the object of <span class="english">can</span> is <span class="english">sing,</span> a verb)

The most common verbs that act on other verbs are a set of five or so verbs that actually can ONLY{{There is a gray zone with words like “want” and “must”. In German, “want” is a modal, but in English, it is a verb. In both, “must” is modal, even though you can also need an object.
}} take verbs as objects. For instance, you <span class="english">I can sing</span> works, but <span class="english">I can the cat</span> has no meaning. These verbs are often called modal verbs in other languages, and usually function in special ways.{{For example, in English, there is no infinitive for modals. you can’t say *“He wants to <b>can</b> go” or *“Will she <b>may</b> visit me?” you have to say “He wants to <b>be able to</b> go” and “Will she <b>be allowed to</b> visit me?” Similarly, in Chinese, you can say “我能唱歌”, but you can’t say *“我<b>想</b>能唱歌”. In German, modals are more like normal verbs, but only modals can have special constructions like “Sie hat das nicht sagen <b>dürfen</b>”. All in all, in many languages, modals function much more like adverbs than verbs, and some analyses don’t treat them as verbs at all.
}} Here is their use in Trevorese:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>the cat <b>can (is able to)</b> talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">can</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat <b>may (is allowed to)</b> talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">can</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat <b>should (ought to)</b> talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">must</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat <b>might (possibly will)</b> talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">may</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


Then there are a lot of other verbs that can act on verbs OR nouns. In English/German/etc., these are treated differently; in Trevorese they are the same as the so-called “true modals”:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>the cat <b>must (has to/needs to)</b> talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">big-want</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat <b>wants to</b> talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">want</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat <b>tries to</b> talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">seek</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat <b>likes to</b> talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">good-energy</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



Important note: You may notice that there is only one do at the end here, and not before the first verb! This is optional (but preferred). You can also explicitly add all the do s:

<div class="table-container"><table border="1">
<thead>
<tr><th>en</th><th>gloss</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>the cat <b>can</b> talk</td><td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">can</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> [normal <span class="gloss">form</span>]<br/><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">can</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> [explicit <span class="gloss">form</span>]</td></tr>
<tr><td>the cat <b>wants to</b> talk</td><td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">want</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> [normal <span class="gloss">form</span>]<br/><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">want</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> [explicit <span class="gloss">form</span>]</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>




Verbs that act on other verbs are incredibly powerful, and capture all the different ways you can perform a noun – including tense!  When we told you about tenses before, we only told you half the story. What we didn’t tell you is that the two tense markers we taught you — <span class="gloss">back</span> and <span class="gloss">front</span> — are in fact themselves just a special case of verbs acting on verbs. Observe:

<div class="table-container"><table border="1">
<thead>
<tr><th>en</th><th>gloss</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>the cat <b>is</b> talk<b>ing</b><br/>the cat <b>talks</b></td><td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td></tr>
<tr><td>the cat <b>did</b> talk<br/>the cat talk<b>ed</b></td><td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td></tr>
<tr><td>the cat <b>will</b> talk<br/>the cat <b>is going to</b> talk</td><td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">front</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td></tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


All these constructions are all formed the same way! And indeed, in Trevorese, there is no difference between “tenses” and “modal verbs”. The concept of a “tense” as it is usually conceived is based on how Indo-European languages work, where tenses are treated in a special way, but modals are treated more like verbs. However, in other languages, it’s not so. In Chinese, Vietnamese, or Malay, tenses are expressed as adverbs, and in Telugu, tenses and modals are in the same category of suffixes!

<h4>multiple verbs acting on verbs</h4>
Want to have multiple verbs acting on another verb? No problem!
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>the cat may be able to talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">may</span> <span class="gloss">can</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat will be able to talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">front</span> <span class="gloss">can</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat should have talked</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">must</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat should be allowed to talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">should</span> <span class="gloss">allowed</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat should not be allowed to talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">no</span> <span class="gloss">should</span> <span class="gloss">allowed</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat should not have been allowed to talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">no</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">should</span> <span class="gloss">allowed</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat should not have been allowed to be able to talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">no</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">should</span> <span class="gloss">allowed</span> <span class="gloss">can</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat should not have been allowed to be able to try to talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">no</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">should</span> <span class="gloss">allowed</span> <span class="gloss">can</span> <span class="gloss">try</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


Does this last sentence look a bit extreme? It’s really not! consider this dialogue:
A: “Hey, you said your organization was going to create a robot, right? How’d that go? Were you going to let it talk to other employees?”
B: “It went terribly. It should not have been allowed to be able to try to talk to others. We shouldn’t have let it even have the capability to initiate conversation.”


<h4>multiple verbs acting on verbs with adverbs in between</h4>
One small example should suffice to show how this is simpler in Trevorese:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>the cat should not be allowed to talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">no</span> <span class="gloss">should</span> <span class="gloss">allowed</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat should not ever be allowed to talk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">no</span> <span class="gloss">should</span> <span class="gloss">allowed</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">one</span> <span class="gloss">time</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>

