<h4>Note on “want” and other verbs that can act on nouns OR verbs</h4>
“Want” is a special word that deserves its own section. You can 1) want something (“want” is a verb), 2) want to do something (“want” is a modal verb); 3) want to be something; or 4) want that something happens.{{  “Want” is often treated oddly. In English it functions as a verb; in German it functions as a modal. In Chinese, you can use 想 only to want a verb, but not a noun. In Arabic, Irish, and Hebrew, there is no verb for wanting; you just say the object of verb is “from you”. And even the English word “want” originally just means to lack.
}} These are straightforward but worth mentioning:
<div class="table-container"><table border="1">
<thead>
<tr><th>en</th><th>gloss</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>the cat wants a mouse</td><td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">want</span> <span class="gloss">bite-animal</span><br/><span class="gloss">deleteme</span></td></tr>
<tr><td>the cat wants to sing</td><td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">want</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">sing</span> [normal <span class="gloss">form</span>]<br/><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">want</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">sing</span> [explicit <span class="gloss">form</span>]</td></tr>
<tr><td>the cat wants to be a mouse</td><td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">want</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">bite-animal</span><br/><span class="gloss">deleteme</span></td></tr>
<tr><td>the cat wants to be able to talk</td><td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">want</span> <span class="gloss">can</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span><br/><span class="gloss">deleteme</span></td></tr>
<tr><td>the cat wants the mouse to be here</td><td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">want</span> <span class="gloss">bite-animal</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">here</span><br/><span class="gloss">deleteme</span></td></tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>




This is the same story for any verb that can take a noun or a verb as its object, like “try”, “like”, “need”, etc.

You may have been confused about this “explicit form” business for when verbs act on other verbs. Now you can see the reasoning more clearly:
normal form (only put “do” before last verb)
clearly signals that you’re wanting an action instead of an object
easier to say (don’t repeat “do”)
explicit form (“do” before every verb)
“the cat wants to sing” and “the cat wants a mouse” are more parallel because they both start with “cat do want”

Overall, you can ignore this though! use whichever one you want.

More examples:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>the cat is a mouse</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">bite-animal</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat wants a mouse</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">want</span> <span class="gloss">bite-animal</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat wants to be a mouse</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">want</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">bite-animal</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat wants like a mouse (does)</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">want</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">bite-animal</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat wants to be like a mouse</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">want</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">bite-animal</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div><h4>More verbs acting on Verbs: the “Instrumental case”</h4>
Many languages have a special way of marking things when they are being used to do something. Trevorese, like Chinese, simply uses “use”. It is just another case of a verb acting on another verb.
<div class="table-container"><table border="1">
<thead>
<tr><th>en</th><th>gloss</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>He <b>used</b> a shovel <b>to dig</b> the hole.</td><td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss-emph">use</span> <span class="gloss">shovel</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">dig</span> <span class="gloss">hole</span> [normal]<br/><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">use</span> <span class="gloss">shovel</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">dig</span> <span class="gloss">hole</span> [explicit]</td></tr>
<tr><td>He <b>dug</b> the hole <b>with</b> a shovel.</td><td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss-emph">use</span> <span class="gloss">shovel</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">dig</span> <span class="gloss">hole</span> [normal]<br/><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">use</span> <span class="gloss">shovel</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">dig</span> <span class="gloss">hole</span> [explicit]</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


Note that the English “with” here is an instrumental marker in English, and actually a quite different meaning from the normal meaning. For the normal meaning of “with”, this would mean “He and a shovel were digging a hole”!

</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Indirect objects</div><div class="collapsible-content">
Some verbs have two objects. Consider the verbs “give” , “say”, “talk”, and “throw”. They can have a single object:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>He gives a gift.</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">give</span> <span class="gloss">gift</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He says a word</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">word</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He talks about work</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">hard-do</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He throws a rock</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">throw</span> <span class="gloss">rock</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He steals a rock</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">steal</span> <span class="gloss">rock</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



However, you can also add a second object with a preposition like <b>to</b> or <b>at.</b> This second object is called the indirect object. Just as English, Trevorese marks these with the preposition “to” (aka <span class="gloss">direction)</span><div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>He gives a gift <b>to me</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">give</span> <span class="gloss">gift</span> <span class="gloss-emph">direction</span> <span class="gloss-emph">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He says a word <b>to me</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">word</span> <span class="gloss-emph">direction</span> <span class="gloss-emph">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He yells <b>at me</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">big-sound-talk</span> <span class="gloss-emph">direction</span> <span class="gloss-emph">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He talks about work <b>to me</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">hard-do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">direction</span> <span class="gloss-emph">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He throws a rock <b>to me</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">throw</span> <span class="gloss">rock</span> <span class="gloss-emph">direction</span> <span class="gloss-emph">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He steals a rock <b>from me</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">steal</span> <span class="gloss">rock</span> <span class="gloss-emph">direction</span> <span class="gloss-emph">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He puts  bag on the table</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">put</span> <span class="gloss">bag</span> <span class="gloss-emph">direction</span> <span class="gloss-emph">top</span> <span class="gloss-emph">table</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


To an English speaker, this should be pretty straightforward: you just indicate the recipient of the verb phrase with <span class="gloss">direction.</span> Why is it worth mentioning? First of all, other languages treat indirect objects differently (e.g. with the Dative case). Second of all, English has another way of  marking the indirect object, just by using the word order:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>He gives <b>me</b> a gift</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">give</span> <span class="gloss">gift</span> <span class="gloss-emph">direction</span> <span class="gloss-emph">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He talks <b>to me</b> about work</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">hard-do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">direction</span> <span class="gloss-emph">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He throws <b>me</b> a rock</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">throw</span> <span class="gloss">rock</span> <span class="gloss-emph">direction</span> <span class="gloss-emph">me</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


In Trevorese, you can never omit the preposition <span class="gloss">direction</span>  for the indirect object.

There are a few verbs in English that use “to” even when it appears to be a direct object. For instance, you talk to someone. However, in these cases this is because there is an implied indirect object: when you talk to someone, you are actually saying words (the direct object) to someone (the indirect object). The situation is the same for Trevorese: for these verbs with implied objects, we use the preposition <span class="gloss">direction:</span><div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>He <b>talks about</b> people</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">talk</span> <span class="gloss">number</span> <span class="gloss">people</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He <b>talks to</b> people</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">talk</span> <span class="gloss-emph">direction</span> <span class="gloss">number</span> <span class="gloss">people</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He <b>writes a</b> letter</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">write</span> <span class="gloss">letter</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He <b>writes about</b> pigs</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">write</span> <span class="gloss">number</span> <span class="gloss">pig</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He <b>writes to</b> me</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">write</span> <span class="gloss-emph">direction</span> <span class="gloss">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Give</b> [<b>to]</b> me the girl!</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">give</span> <span class="gloss">girl</span> <span class="gloss-emph">direction</span> <span class="gloss">me</span>!</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Give me to</b>the girl!</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">give</span> <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss-emph">direction</span> <span class="gloss">girl</span>!</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


This point should not pose problems for speakers of English: they should just translate “to” into <span class="gloss">direction.</span> This should be familiar also to speakers of Chinese, where direction can be interpreted as 对: one can see that above, the treatment of <span class="english">to talk</span> is the same as Chinese 说 vs 说对.

Note 1: In Chinese, there is the exact same phenomenon, where if there is no particle, the first object is the indirect object and the second is direct (I give you a thing / 我给你一个东西). if you invert the order of the objects but want the same meaning, you need to add a particle (I give a thing <b>to</b> you / 我<b>把</b>一个东西给你). However, instead of marking the indirect object, Chinese marks the direct object.

When speaking, we need some way to differentiate between these two objects.  For example, “give me to the girl” and  “give me the girl”  are very different sentences.

Note 2: Interestingly, in English there are also verbs where you are not allowed to use the word order, and you have to use a preposition. Consider the word <span class="english">say.</span> While you can say <span class="english">Give me the cat</span>, you can’t say <span class="wrong">*Say me the thing</span>.


Exercise:
<div class="table-container"><table border="1">
<thead>
<tr><th>en</th><th>gloss</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>He gives a gift</td><td></td></tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


He gives a gift to me.


He gives me a gift


He talks about cats


He talks to me about cats


He talks about cats to me


He talks to cats about me


He says a word


He says a word to me


He throws a rock


He throws a rock at me


He throws the rock to me


He puts  bag on the table





</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Verbs 4: Infinitives and gerunds</div><div class="collapsible-content">
In Indo-European languages like English, verbs have a special form called the infinitive, which is used in certain situations when there isn’t a subject doing the verb. In English, you can often use the gerund (-ing form) in similar ways.

Many situations where IE languages use the infinitive is when you have a verb acting on another verb. We already saw how to do this:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>the cat wants the mouse <b>to be</b> here</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> [do] <span class="gloss">want</span> <span class="gloss">bite-animal</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">be</span> <span class="gloss">here</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>She doesn’t like <b>walking</b> / She doesn’t like <b>to walk</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">no</span> [do] <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">go-arm-go</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He thinks of <b>talking</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> [do] <span class="gloss">think</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">talk</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



Another situation where IE languages use an infinitive or gerund is when you are referring to the general state of a verb, as in “walking is good” or “It is good to walk.”. In this case, the verb has become a sort of noun, meaning “the state of walking”. In Trevorese, we just need to add the “do” to show that it is a verb, and then you can use it like any other noun:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><b>Walking</b> is good / It is good <b>to walk</b>.</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">go-arm-go</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">good</span>.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He thinks <b>talking</b> is hard / it is hard <b>to talk</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">think</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">talk</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">no-easy</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>Being</b> a student is fun / It is fun <b>to be</b> a student.</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">be</span> <span class="gloss">get-know-person</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">good-time</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>You <b>being</b> here makes me happy.</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">be</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">place</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">make</span> <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">good-energy</span>.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>The fact that you are</b> here makes me happy.</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">be</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">place</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">make</span> <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">good-energy</span>.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


Serendipitously, this ends up sounding similar to the English construction “to Verb”!

Finally, there are situations in English where gerunds like <span class="english">being</span> pop up just because English uses “to be” for adjectives as well:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>He was being cute</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">cute</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>She is being mean to me</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">mean</span> <span class="gloss-emph">direction</span> <span class="gloss">me</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Verbs 5: Clauses and conjunctions</div><div class="collapsible-content">

The most basic way to make two clauses in Trevorese is to just put two sentences one after the other:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>I told you</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">say</span> <span class="gloss">you</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>the cat talked</td>
<td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I told you (that) the cat talked</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">say</span>, <span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


In English, we can optionally put a “that” in there to make the causality clear. In Trevorese, as in Chinese, there is no such word and you just put the clauses next to each other. Of course, you can also use conjunctions to connect two clauses:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>I told you, <b>but</b> the cat talked</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">say</span> <span class="gloss">you</span>, <span class="gloss-emph">against</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I told you, <b>and</b> the cat talked</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">say</span> <span class="gloss">you</span>, <span class="gloss-emph">also</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I told you, <b>so</b> the cat talked</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">say</span> <span class="gloss">you</span>, <span class="gloss-emph">then</span> <span class="gloss-emph">this-reason</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I told you <b>after</b> the cat talked</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">say</span> <span class="gloss">you</span>, <span class="gloss-emph">after</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">other</div><div class="collapsible-content">
“other” is the last of the quantifiers we haven’t introduced:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>I saw a <b>another</b> cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">see</span> <span class="gloss-emph">other</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>The <b>other</b> cat was smaller</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">other</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">small</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">over</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Self, own, each other</div><div class="collapsible-content">

If the subject of a verb is the same as an object, you can use “self”. It doesn’t get tangled weirdly into verbs like Spanish “se” or German “sich”. Using “self” doesn’t change the meaning of the verb at all.
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>he washed the towel</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">no-dirt</span> <span class="gloss">water-flat-stuff</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>he washed <b>himself</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">no-dirt</span> <span class="gloss-emph">self</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>they washed <b>themselves</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">number</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">no-dirt</span> <span class="gloss-emph">self</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



The English word “own”, in the sense of “their own”, really means “of their self”. It is expressed this way in Trevorese (as it is in Chinese):
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>he ate <b>his own</b> feces</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">eat</span> <span class="gloss">feces</span> <span class="gloss-emph">of</span> <span class="gloss-emph">self</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>she didn't know <b>her own</b> name</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">no</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">knowledge</span> <span class="gloss">name</span> <span class="gloss-emph">of</span> <span class="gloss-emph">self</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



To express “each other”, use “other self”:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>they flog <b>themselves</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">number</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">flog</span> <span class="gloss-emph">self</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>they flog <b>each other</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">number</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">flog</span> <span class="gloss-emph">other</span> <span class="gloss-emph">self</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div><h4>Emphasis</h4>
English has a messy system of stressing a word with tone. Trevorese adopts the more common approach of adding a particle after a word to stress it, and this word is “self”, much like how in English, we might say “he himself said so”, or “he himself admitted himself that he suck”.
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>what did you say?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">what</span> <span class="gloss">thing</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>You said <b>WHAT?</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">what</span> <span class="gloss-emph">thing</span> <span class="gloss-emph">self</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>YOU</b> said what?</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">you</span> <span class="gloss-emph">self</span> <span class="gloss-emph">back</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">what</span> <span class="gloss">thing</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>even you</b> said that.</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">you</span> <span class="gloss-emph">self</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">that</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><b>you only</b> said that. [Indian English]</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">you</span> <span class="gloss-emph">self</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">that</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>you <b>even said</b> that</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">talk</span> <span class="gloss-emph">self</span> <span class="gloss">that</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>you said <b>even that</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss-emph">that</span> <span class="gloss-emph">self</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


This also ends up sounding like the emphatic clitics in Irish.


TODO nice green italic highlight:
You have now essentially learned the whole grammar! The next chapter will be helping you understand how to fit the complex grammar of your native language into this simple, yet fully expressive, language.

</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">also, again</div><div class="collapsible-content">
Also is a funny little word that basically just adds some emphasis. It’s a regular adjective/adverb in Trevorese, like in English:

<div class="table-container"><table border="1">
<thead>
<tr><th>en</th><th>gloss</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>I <b>also</b> saw a cat<br/>I <b>too</b> saw a cat<br/>I saw a cat <b>as well</b></td><td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">see</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">also</span></td></tr>
<tr><td>The cat is <b>also</b> small<br/>The cat is small <b>as well</b><br/>-</td><td><span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">small</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">also</span></td></tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



Again is also a straightforward adverb:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>I saw a cat <b>again</b></td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">see</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">other-time</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Disambiguation forms</div><div class="collapsible-content">
TODO finish this and maybe put it in the lexicon section

Many Trevorese terms are more ambiguous than English terms. For instance, <span class="gloss">person</span> means any being, either human or animal; and <span class="gloss">ball</span> means either a sphere or a circle. In 90% of the cases, these are unambiguous in context. However, what do you do if you really need to specify that something is a circle, not a sphere? In this case you can use the more explicit form, known as the disambiguation form. For instance:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>sphere/circle</td>
<td><span class="gloss">ball</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>sphere</td>
<td><span class="gloss">body-ball</span> (aka <span class="gloss">3d-ball</span>)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>circle</td>
<td><span class="gloss">equal-ball</span> (aka <span class="gloss">flat-ball</span>)</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="section-h2"><div class="collapsible-header">Grammar 3: fitting the complexity of natural languages into the grammar you have just finished learning</div>
<div class="collapsible-content">
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Parts of speech</div><div class="collapsible-content">
You may have noticed this already, but in Trevorese, most words are nouns. A verb is just “doing” a noun, and an adjective is just being “like” a noun. Therefore, there are only the following parts of speech:

<ol>
<li>nouns (and pronouns)
    <ol type="a">
<li>verbs: “do noun”</li>
<li> modals: like verbs</li>
<li> conjunctions: noun placed before clause</li>
<li> prepositions: nouns placed before other nouns</li>
<li> quantifiers: special nouns placed before other nouns (this/that/etc, “more”, “sixty-seven”…)</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>Special markers: “do”, “like”
    <ol type="a"><li>technically also nouns maybe?</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Other tenses with special Adverbs</div><div class="collapsible-content">
The second important subtlety to using verbs well is adverbs. Let’s introduce a few very important adverbs:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>usually</td>
<td><span class="gloss">custom</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>ever</td>
<td><span class="gloss">times</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>already</td>
<td><span class="gloss">before</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>just</td>
<td><span class="gloss">just</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



These allow us to express other tenses in various languages. Let’s look at them one-by-one:

<span class="gloss">custom</span> is used for any habitual action: just use it as an adverb modifying the verb, e.g. &lt;you normally go&gt; “<span class="gloss">you do go like custom</span>”. In English, this is expressed with “used to” in the past tense, by the simple present tense or “usually” in the present, and by the progressive “-ing” in in the future:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>I am walking to school</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">go-arm-go</span> <span class="gloss">direction</span> <span class="gloss">learn-place</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I [usually] walk to school</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">go-arm-go</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">custom</span> <span class="gloss">direction</span> <span class="gloss">learn-place</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I used to walk to school</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">go-arm-go</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">custom</span> <span class="gloss">direction</span> <span class="gloss">learn-place</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I will be [regularly] walking to school</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">will</span> <span class="gloss">go-arm-go</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">custom</span> <span class="gloss">direction</span> <span class="gloss">learn-place</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div><span class="gloss">just</span> is used exactly as the English “just”, to express a time very close to the present. However, English needs a lot of extra words to express this when combined with different tenses:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>I just walked to school</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">go-arm-go</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">just</span> <span class="gloss">direction</span> <span class="gloss">learn-place</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I am just now walking to school</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">go-arm-go</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">just</span> <span class="gloss">direction</span> <span class="gloss">learn-place</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I am just about to walk to school</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">go-arm-go</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">just</span> <span class="gloss">direction</span> <span class="gloss">learn-place</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



English has a tense called the perfect (“have”),{{ Most Indo-European languages have this, but it has different meanings in them, leading to confusion for learners. In Spanish, “he comido” carries the connotation that it just happened, and in German it is the default past tense, so “Ich bin gelaufen” just means “I ran”.
}} as in the sentence “I have been to Germany” or “More people have been to Berlin than me”. All this is really conveying is that the action has, indeed, happened at least once, and likely many times, in contrast to a statement like “I went to Germany”, which just means you went a particular time. So in effect, the perfect is just saying that you went some time(s).

At this point we introduce the Trevorese word <span class="gloss">times:</span><div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>I fell</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">down</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I fell once</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">down</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">one</span> <span class="gloss">times</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I fell twice</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">down</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">two</span> <span class="gloss">times</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I fell 67 times</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">down</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">six-seven</span> <span class="gloss">times</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I fell several times</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">down</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">number</span> <span class="gloss">times</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



If you use times without any quantifier, it just means “one or more times”:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>I fell some number of times</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">down</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">times</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


However, English has a different way of expressing this: the perfect tense! Hence:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>I have fallen</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">down</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">times</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I have walked to school</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">go-arm-go</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">times</span> <span class="gloss">direction</span> <span class="gloss">learn-place</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I have walked to school twice</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">go-arm-go</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">two</span> <span class="gloss-emph">times</span> <span class="gloss">direction</span> <span class="gloss">learn-place</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



English also has the curiously named tense, the pluperfect (the “had verbed” tense). This is specifically used for things that happened in the past and were already completed before another thing happened in the past — it’s kind of like “the past with respect to the past”. However, there is also a much simpler way of expressing the same thing in English: “already”. Trevorese takes this approach, with <span class="gloss">already:</span><div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>I had walked to school, but he didn’t know</td>
<td><span class="gloss">I</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">go-arm-go</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">before</span> <span class="gloss">to</span> <span class="gloss">learn-place</span>, <span class="gloss">against</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">not</span> [past] <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">know</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Future Perfect Tense</div><div class="collapsible-content">
The future perfect tense, or “past within future”, is a feature of Indo-European languages that occurs in dependent clauses. In Trevorese, it is simply expressed with the past:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Next year we <b>will have bought</b> two dogs</td>
<td>&lt;Next <span class="gloss">year</span> <span class="gloss">we</span> <span class="gloss">did</span> <span class="gloss">buy</span> <span class="gloss">two</span> <span class="gloss">dogs</span>&gt; <span class="gloss">year</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">next</span> <span class="gloss">number</span> <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss-emph">back</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">buy</span> <span class="gloss">two</span> <span class="gloss">dog</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



The context makes it clear that this “we did buy two dogs” is happening relative to the future, i.e. “next year”. Conversely, one can just as easily form the “future within past” tense!
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Last year we <b>were going to buy</b> two dogs</td>
<td>&lt;Last <span class="gloss">year</span> <span class="gloss">we</span> <span class="gloss">will</span> <span class="gloss">buy</span> <span class="gloss">two</span> <span class="gloss">dogs</span>&gt; <span class="gloss">year</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">last</span> <span class="gloss">number</span> <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss-emph">will</span> <span class="gloss-emph">buy</span> <span class="gloss">two</span> <span class="gloss">dog</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He said that he <b>would sing</b></td>
<td>&lt;He <span class="gloss">said</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">will</span> <span class="gloss">singglt</span>; <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">say</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss-emph">will</span> <span class="gloss-emph">sing</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



The future-within-past in English has to be expressed with this rather cumbersome “were going to” construction, or the verb “would” which is ambiguous because “would” also has the separate meaning of the conditional mode.

Als please consider this sentence:

Next year we were going to buy two dogs, but we decided not to


</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Past participles</div><div class="collapsible-content">
The past participle in English expresses that a verb happened to some noun. It is a special way of making a verb into an adjective. In many cases, this is TODO TODO
<ul><li>me like stress</li><li>situation like stress</li><li>apple like fall</li><li>apple like eat like half</li></ul>
In Trevorese, this is treated no differently than any other adjective phrase: it is accomplished by a like phrase with the past tense:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>A <b>fallen</b> apple</td>
<td><span class="gloss">apple</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">this</span> <span class="gloss-emph">back</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss-emph">down</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



In English, past participles can also mean that “something did this”. In Trevorese, the construction is the same as before, but with a “<span class="gloss">some”:</span><div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>A <b>half-eaten</b> apple</td>
<td><span class="gloss">apple</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> [some] <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">eat</span> <span class="gloss">half</span> [of <span class="gloss">this</span>]</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



The words in brackets are optional; as in most languages, they can be left out.

In English, past participles are a special construction only for the past participle of a verb. But in Trevorese, there is no difference between the past tense and other modals, so this same construction can be used for all the modals:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>An apple that is about to fall</td>
<td><span class="gloss">apple</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> [this] <span class="gloss">will</span> <span class="gloss">down</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>An apple that is about to be eaten</td>
<td><span class="gloss">apple</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> [some] <span class="gloss">will</span> <span class="gloss">eat</span> [this]</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>An apple that can fall</td>
<td><span class="gloss">apple</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> [this] <span class="gloss">can</span> <span class="gloss">down</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>An edible apple</td>
<td><span class="gloss">apple</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> [some] <span class="gloss">can</span> <span class="gloss">eat</span> [this]</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>An apple that may be edible</td>
<td><span class="gloss">apple</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> [some] <span class="gloss">may</span> <span class="gloss">can</span> <span class="gloss">eat</span> [this]</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



Observe that English has all sorts of different constructions for these!


</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Counterfactuals</div><div class="collapsible-content"><h4>The Conditional and “if”</h4>
The conditional is a special tense (or “mood” if you’re a purist) that crops up in some languages.  It’s basically identical to talking about things that would happen. In English, it’s most noticeable when it changes “will” into “would”, meaning “will go, conditional on that first statement”.

This is simple enough in Trevorese: we just use case, which is identical to “if”. Essentially, it means “In the case that…”
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>[future] if he sings, I will hear him</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">case</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss-emph">front</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">sing</span>, <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss-emph">front</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">sound-see</span> <span class="gloss">this</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>[present] if he is singing, I hear him</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">case</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">sing</span>, <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">sound-see</span> <span class="gloss">this</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>[past] if he were singing, I heard him</td>
<td><span class="gloss-emph">case</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss-emph">back</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">sing</span>, <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss-emph">back</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">sound-see</span> <span class="gloss">this</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


Note: the “sing” in  “if you sing, I will hear you”, even though it looks like the present tense, is actually in the future. Trevorese treats it as such.

<h4>The Subjunctive</h4>
The subjunctive happens when there is something that is happening counterfactually. For instance, in none of the sentences “If you were to come”, “If you had come”, and “I hope you come” did you actually come. Many languages, for instance Indo-European languages, have all sorts of complex ways of dealing with this situation. Trevorese, like Chinese, Telugu, Toki Pona, and so on, sidesteps this and leaves them ambiguous:


<div class="table-container"><table border="1">
<thead>
<tr><th>en</th><th>gloss</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>[future] if he sings, I will hear him<br/>[future subj.] if he were to sing, I would hear him<br/>deleteme<br/>deleteme</td><td> <span class="gloss-emph">case</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss-emph">front</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">sing</span>, <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss-emph">front</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">sound-see</span> <span class="gloss">this</span></td></tr>
<tr><td>[present] if he is singing, I hear him<br/>[present subj.] if he were singing, I would hear him<br/>deleteme<br/>deleteme</td><td> <span class="gloss-emph">case</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">sing</span>, <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">sound-see</span> <span class="gloss">this</span></td></tr>
<tr><td>[past] if he was singing, I heard him<br/>[past subj.] if he had been singing, I would have heard him<br/>[past subj.] if he had sung, I would have heard him<br/>[past subj.] if he would of sung, I would have heard him</td><td><span class="gloss-emph">case</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss-emph">back</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">sing</span>, <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss-emph">back</span> <span class="gloss-emph">do</span> <span class="gloss">sound-see</span> <span class="gloss">this</span></td></tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>






Note that the second part of the clause would be, in English, in the conditional. Conditional and subjunctive go together like bread and butter! But as we already established, there is no conditional in Trevorese, so the second half of the clause is just in normal indicative.

Now, in some cases, the fact that the subjunctive and the indicative are the same may be annoying. The default interpretation is that we are talking about a subjunctive event. If we really need to clarify, we can add “in fact” to be clear that the statement is in the indicative:
<div class="table-container"><table border="1">
<thead>
<tr><th>en</th><th>gloss</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>[past] if he was singing, I heard him<br/>[past subj.] if he had been singing, I would have heard him</td><td><span class="gloss">case</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">sing</span>, <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">sound-see</span> <span class="gloss">this</span></td></tr>
<tr><td>[past] if he was <b>in fact</b> singing, I heard him<br/>deleteme</td><td><span class="gloss">case</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">sing</span> <span class="gloss-emph">like</span> <span class="gloss-emph">true</span>, <span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">sound-see</span> <span class="gloss">this</span></td></tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">“It”: Passive voice</div><div class="collapsible-content">
German uses even more “it: than English, e.g. “It gonged”, “It is whispered in the ear”. Irish has its own conjugation, e.g. “déartear” – it is said.

The passive is a somewhat unusual construction that crops up in some form or other in many languages. It can either be used to omit a subject, or to take responsibility away from them. Let’s look at the first example first.

Any language needs some way to have sentences that don’t have a clear subject. Consider the following sentence:

the milk was spilled

All this is saying is that someone or something spilled the milk, but the speaker is not saying who. Fortunately, Trevorese has a pronoun for someone or something: <span class="gloss">some.</span> Therefore, the passive can be expressed much more simply than in English:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>the milk was spilled</td>
<td><span class="gloss">some</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">spill</span> <span class="gloss">milk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>someone or something spilled the milk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">some</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">spill</span> <span class="gloss">milk</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



Note English expresses this in the exact same way, if you care to express whether the doer was animate or inanimate, i.e. whether it was a person or thing. (TODO link that other chapter.) The same can be done in Trevorese:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>someone spilled the milk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">some</span> <span class="gloss">person</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">spill</span> <span class="gloss">milk</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>something spilled the milk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">some</span> <span class="gloss">thing</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">spill</span> <span class="gloss">milk</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



Now, what about the version of the passive that has a subject attached to it?

<ul><li>the milk was spilled by Fred</li></ul>
The only difference between this and the active voice is that it takes some responsibility away from Fred. This distinction doesn’t add much to the expressivity of the language, and can safely be removed. As such, Trevorese just uses the active voice in these constructions:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>the milk was spilled by Fred</td>
<td><span class="gloss">Fred</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">spill</span> <span class="gloss">cow-water</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Fred spilled the milk</td>
<td><span class="gloss">Fred</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">spill</span> <span class="gloss">cow-water</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Who was the milk spilled by?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">what</span> <span class="gloss">person</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">spill</span> <span class="gloss">cow-water</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Who spilled the milk?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">what</span> <span class="gloss">person</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">spill</span> <span class="gloss">cow-water</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td> <span class="wrong"> *It is calling someone my name </span> </td>
<td><span class="gloss">some</span> <span class="gloss">person</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">call</span> <span class="gloss">name</span> <span class="gloss">of</span> <span class="gloss">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Her nose likes being kissed</td>
<td><span class="gloss">face-point</span> <span class="gloss">of</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">enjoy</span> <span class="gloss-emph">some</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">kiss</span> [this]</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Her nose likes being kissed by me</td>
<td><span class="gloss">face-point</span> <span class="gloss">of</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">enjoy</span> <span class="gloss-emph">me</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">kiss</span> [this]</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



This last sentence is not grammatical in English, but it is normal in German!



</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">“It”: Impersonal Aspect</div><div class="collapsible-content">
    Similar to the passive, the impersonal aspect is another way to avoid saying the subject. This comes up when there isn’t a subject, for instance for weather. With it is raining or it is dark, there is not really anything that the it refers to, excepting perhaps the universe itself. The only reason that “it” is added is because the grammar of the language demands some subject for the verb. In a language like Spanish, where subjects are not necessary, the subject is simply omitted: llueve means it rains. You can’t say  <span class="wrong">*él llueve</span> or something like that. Hebrew is the same (pro-drop).

Although grammarians tend to think of the impersonal aspect as different from the passive voice, the authors of this work contend that they are actually the same. The only difference is that for the impersonal aspect, one is forced to omit the subject because there isn’t a subject, whereas for the passive, you choose to, because you don’t know who the subject is (or don’t want to say).

What do we do in Trevorese? We just use <span class="gloss">this,</span> in the sense of “this all is raining”. You can think of this use of “this” as someone gesturing in front of them and saying “all of this”.


impersonal with verb:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>It is raining</td>
<td>&lt;this <span class="gloss">is</span> <span class="gloss">doing</span> <span class="gloss">rain</span>&gt; <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">rain</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>It is getting dark</td>
<td>&lt;this <span class="gloss">is</span> <span class="gloss">doing</span> <span class="gloss">dark</span>&gt; <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">dark</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td> <span class="wrong">*It gongs </span> [a gong noise is happening]</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">gong</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>


This last sentence is not grammatical in English, but it is normal in German!

Impersonal with adjective:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>It is dark</td>
<td>&lt;this <span class="gloss">is</span> <span class="gloss">dark</span>&gt; <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">dark</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



In some cases, using <span class="gloss">this</span> may seem ambiguous, if there is already another <span class="gloss">this</span> in the sentence, for instance a person. For instance, imagine we are talking about some guy:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>He walked into the room. It was dark.</td>
<td>&lt;this <span class="gloss">walked</span> <span class="gloss">into</span> <span class="gloss">room</span>. <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">is</span> <span class="gloss">dark</span>&gt;</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>It was raining as he walked.</td>
<td>&lt;this <span class="gloss">was</span> <span class="gloss">raining</span> <span class="gloss">as</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">walked</span>.&gt;</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div><div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>It walked into the room. It was dark.</td>
<td>&lt;this <span class="gloss">walked</span> <span class="gloss">into</span> <span class="gloss">room</span>. <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">is</span> <span class="gloss">dark</span>&gt;</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>It was raining as it walked.</td>
<td>&lt;this <span class="gloss">was</span> <span class="gloss">raining</span> <span class="gloss">as</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">walked</span>.&gt;</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div><h4>There is / there are</h4>
“There is” is expressed just like the other impersonal pronouns, as “this do be”:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>There are a lot of people in the mall</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">big-number</span> <span class="gloss">person</span> <span class="gloss">in</span> <span class="gloss">mall</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="section-h2"><div class="collapsible-header">Grammar 4: focus on various more specific things that crop up in English</div>
<div class="collapsible-content">
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">“Whether”</div><div class="collapsible-content">
“Whether” is a funny word in English. Basically, it just introduces a clause that is a yes-no question. Trevorese, like Chinese, does this much more simply.

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Do you know whether that’s a dog?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">know</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">dog</span> <span class="gloss">what</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>He asked whether it was a dog</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">ask</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">dog</span> <span class="gloss">what</span>?</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Animacy</div><div class="collapsible-content">
Many languages treat nouns differently depending on whether they are animate (e.g. animals) or not (e.g. rocks), and may even have different articles. English uses the animate/inanimate distinction for some words, e.g. who vs what, him vs it, someone vs. something, young vs new. Trevorese does not make this distinction in any cases, but if clarity is needed, “thing” or “being” can be added in:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>what/whom do you see?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">see</span> <span class="gloss">what</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>what do you see?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">see</span> <span class="gloss">what</span> <span class="gloss">thing</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>whom do you see?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">see</span> <span class="gloss">what</span> <span class="gloss">person</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>a young person wears a new hat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">person</span> <span class="gloss">new</span> <span class="gloss">DO</span> <span class="gloss">wear</span> <span class="gloss">hat</span> <span class="gloss">new</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">“It” as “that”</div><div class="collapsible-content">
A special case of the impersonal are expressions like “it is a pig!”, when “it” basically means the same thing as “that” or “this” anyways: even in English, this is more or less the same as saying “This is a pig!”.

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>What’s that? It’s a pig!</td>
<td>&lt;What <span class="gloss">is</span> <span class="gloss">that</span>? <span class="gloss">That</span>’s <span class="gloss">a</span> <span class="gloss">pig</span>!&gt; <span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">what</span>? <span class="gloss">That</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">pig</span>!</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Who’s at the door? It’s your mom!</td>
<td>&lt;What <span class="gloss">is</span> <span class="gloss">at</span> <span class="gloss">door</span>? <span class="gloss">This</span> <span class="gloss">is</span> <span class="gloss">your</span> <span class="gloss">mom</span>&gt; <span class="gloss">what</span> <span class="gloss">person</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">at</span> <span class="gloss">door</span>? <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">be</span> <span class="gloss">mom</span> <span class="gloss">of</span> <span class="gloss">you</span>!</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>It’s a boy!</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> (do <span class="gloss">be</span>) <span class="gloss">boy</span>!</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">“It”/“you”/“They”: “People”</div><div class="collapsible-content">
They say that this “passive”/“impersonal” phenomenon is a deep conspiracy that cuts across all pronouns. It’s everywhere. You can’t get away from it. Whether one recognizes it or not, the spectrum of impersonal phenomena extends deep into the language…or so it is said.

In reality, you can just translate these however you want. Just listing them here for completeness:

<ul><li>It is generally believed that X</li><li>you never know what’s going to happen</li><li>You know what they say</li><li>People are worried</li></ul>
Hebrew: “they say” but with pro-drop. Prodrop implies third if no context.


</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Yes and no</div><div class="collapsible-content">
Trevorese has one word for yes and one word for no:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Are you happy?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">happy</span> <span class="gloss">what</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>yes.</td>
<td><span class="gloss">truth</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>no.</td>
<td><span class="gloss">no</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



These are the same as the words for “correct” and “incorrect”:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Are you happy?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">happy</span> <span class="gloss">what</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>correct.</td>
<td><span class="gloss">truth</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>incorrect.</td>
<td><span class="gloss">no</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



English speakers or Spanish speakers may be confused as to why this gets its own section. How complex can “yes” and “no” be? However, “yes” and “no” are by no means a common phenomenon in language. Latin, Irish, Chinese, Toki Pona, and many others have no word for yes or no: they just repeat the verb. Hence why you see in Hiberno English, whose substrate is irish, exchanges like the following

<ul><li>do you want tea?<ul><li>I do. (Not “yes”)</li></ul></li></ul>
There are also many languages with more than two words for yes or no. French uses the word si when saying yes and contradicting something. German uses the word doch to contradict the thing that was just said, so it can mean either yes or no depending on the context. Older English had four words: TODO. Child English also has four: yes, no, yuh-huh, nuh-huh. (Note that these are different from “m-hm” and “m-m”, which are forms of “u-huh” and “uh-uh”, which simply mean “yes” and “no”.)

In Trevorese, if you want to emphasize that you are contradicting a statement, you can add “but” before it:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>You are studying?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">study</span> <span class="gloss">what</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>yes.</td>
<td><span class="gloss">truth</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>You are studying Chinese, right?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">study</span> <span class="gloss">Chinese</span> <span class="gloss">what</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>but no! I’m studying Trevorese.</td>
<td><span class="gloss">against</span> <span class="gloss">no</span>! <span class="gloss">i</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">study</span> <span class="gloss">Trevorese</span>.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Verbs with implied motion</div><div class="collapsible-content">
In many languages, like English, many verbs are identical save for the directionality, like come/go, bring/take. In Trevorese, there is only one verb for each, and if context is needed, <span class="gloss">that</span><span class="gloss">way</span> and <span class="gloss">this</span><span class="gloss">way</span> are added.

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>she came to my house</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">go</span> <span class="gloss">big-container</span> <span class="gloss">of</span> <span class="gloss">me</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>she went to the store</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">go</span> [that <span class="gloss">way</span>] <span class="gloss">store</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>she came to the store</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">go</span> [this <span class="gloss">way</span>] <span class="gloss">store</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>she carried an apple</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">carry</span> <span class="gloss">apple</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>she brought an apple to the store</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">carry</span> <span class="gloss">apple</span> <span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">way</span> <span class="gloss">to</span> <span class="gloss">store</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>she took an apple from the store</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">carry</span> <span class="gloss">apple</span> <span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">way</span> <span class="gloss">from</span> <span class="gloss">store</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">verbing nouns</div><div class="collapsible-content">
In English, there are a variety of bespoke verbs to verbify different nouns. For instance, you <b>play</b> a violin, you <b>do</b> pushups, you <b>sing</b> a song. In Trevorese, these are all omitted. You just use the <span class="gloss">do</span> particle to indicate that it is a verb:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>She plays piano</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">piano</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>She does pushups</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">number</span> <span class="gloss">pushup</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">To have, to want, to try</div><div class="collapsible-content">
These are verbs that are absent in many languages. Trevorese has them.

</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">too vs very contrast</div><div class="collapsible-content">
Several languages, like Hindi and Chinese, don’t differentiate “too” and “very”. This seems like an odd failing. Trevorese distinguishes them. “Too” is “overmore”
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">“one” and “some”</div><div class="collapsible-content">
In English, we can use “one” to refer to something that has already been mentioned in conversation, or “some” to refer to a plural thing that has already been mentioned in conversation. In Trevorese, this is identical: <span class="gloss">one</span> and <span class="gloss">number</span> are used:

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>I saw a bird. Did you see one?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">see</span> <span class="gloss">air-animal</span>. <span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">see</span> <span class="gloss">one</span> <span class="gloss">what</span>?</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I saw one</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">see</span> <span class="gloss">one</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I saw some</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">see</span> <span class="gloss">pl</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Alone, Only</div><div class="collapsible-content">
These are just adverbs of “one”: todo maybe “like one person”

<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>he was sitting alone</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">sit</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">one</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>he was only sitting</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">sit</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">one</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I only talked to you</td>
<td>??</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>I only want one thing</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">want</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">one</span> <span class="gloss">one</span> <span class="gloss">thing</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>he washed himself alone</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">no-dirt</span> <span class="gloss">self</span> <span class="gloss">like</span> <span class="gloss">one</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div></div>
<div class="section-h3"><div class="collapsible-header">Beyond this and that</div><div class="collapsible-content">
Sometimes one needs to refer to two different subjects, and to differentiate them, you need to use “this” and “that”:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>which cat are you talking about? This one or that one?</td>
<td><span class="gloss">you</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">talk</span> <span class="gloss">what</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span>? <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">other-thing</span> <span class="gloss">that</span>?</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>



However, if you have more than two subjects, this gets rather confusing to deal with in English, and we usually say use emphasis. In Trevorese you can simply say “that-two”, “that-three”, and so on:
<div class="table-container"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>en</th>
<th>gloss</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>I see this cat, that cat, the other cat, and the other other cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">me</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">see</span> <span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span>, <span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span>, <span class="gloss">that-two</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span>, <span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">three</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>this cat meowed at that cat, and then THAT cat meowed at that cat</td>
<td><span class="gloss">this</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">cat-sound</span> <span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span>, <span class="gloss">and</span> <span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">time</span> <span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">two</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span> <span class="gloss">back</span> <span class="gloss">do</span> <span class="gloss">cat-sound</span> <span class="gloss">that</span> <span class="gloss">cat</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div><script>
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
    // Initialize all collapsible sections
    initializeCollapsibleSections();
});

function initializeCollapsibleSections() {
    // Add click event to all collapsible headers
    const headers = document.querySelectorAll('.collapsible-header');
    
    headers.forEach(header => {
        header.addEventListener('click', function() {
            // Toggle the 'open' class on the header
            this.classList.toggle('open');
            
            // Find the next sibling which is the content container
            const content = this.nextElementSibling;
            if (content && content.classList.contains('collapsible-content')) {
                content.classList.toggle('open');
            }
        });
    });
    
    // Open all H2 sections by default (table of contents view)
    const h2Headers = document.querySelectorAll('.section-h2 > .collapsible-header');
    h2Headers.forEach(header => {
        // Don’t open the content, just show the headers
        header.classList.add('open');
    });
}
</script>
</div>
</div>
</div>
